<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06289188 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06289188 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Milosevic; PHOTO: Tudjman  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  USSR; LEADER; ASSAULT; END; YUGOSLAVIA  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The leaders of the warring republics of Serbia and Croatia arrived today fortalks with Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev to seek ways to end theconflict, a presidential spokesman said.;   &quot;We hope to take steps to lessenthe tension,&quot; Andrei Grachev said, adding: &quot;Gorbachev does not have anyspecific, detailed peace plan, and it's possible that very little could bedone.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GORBACHEV BIDS TO MEDIATE IN YUGOSLAVIA  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Gorbachev scheduled separate meetings with Slobodan Milosevic, thepresident of Serbia, and Franjo Tudjman, the president of secessionistCroatia.;   The Soviet president hoped to get the leaders to agree to ameeting, possibly in Moscow, that &quot;could be the starting point for astabilization process,&quot; Grachev said.;   Gorbachev appealed to Yugoslavia'spolitical and military leaders last week to avoid escalating the civil war andcalled on them to &quot;display maximum responsibility and restraint.&quot;;   Fearshave been expressed in the Soviet Union that the splintering superpower, whichis beset by ethnic conflicts, could end up like Yugoslavia. Gorbachev raisedsuch a possibility in July with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.;   The Sovietnews agency Tass quoted Tudjman as saying he came to Moscow to informGorbachev and Russian President Boris Yeltsin &quot;about details of the Yugoslavcrisis and the war now being waged against Croatia.&quot;;   He said he hoped thatMoscow mediation could &quot;help stop this bloody conflict.&quot;;   Milosevic, in aninterview with Tass, said he was looking forward to constructive negotiations.&quot;We hope the mediation of Moscow, with which we have always had goodrelations, will be successful,&quot; he was quoted as saying.  </